    <h1>Interest Rate Models</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">MIT OCW 18.S096 + 15.450 (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Interest rates are not stocks&mdash;they <strong>mean-revert</strong>. A 15% rate pulls back toward some long-run level; a negative rate pushes up. The right model encodes this pull while keeping rates from reaching unrealistically extreme negative values. (Mildly negative nominal rates have occurred in practice, but the Vasicek model's Gaussian tails can push rates far below zero.)</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: mean-reverting rate paths -->
