    <!-- 1. Vasicek Model -->
    <h3>Vasicek model</h3>
    <p>The Vasicek model is the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process applied to interest rates: dr = &#x3BA;(&#x3B8; &#x2212; r)dt + &#x3C3;dW. The speed of mean reversion &#x3BA; controls how fast rates snap back to the long-run mean &#x3B8;. The drawback: rates can go negative because the noise term is additive.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Vasicek model: dr = kappa*(theta - r)*dt + sigma*dW
; Euler discretization

(define (vasicek-step r kappa theta sigma dt z)
  (+ r (* kappa (- theta r) dt) (* sigma (sqrt dt) z)))

; Parameters
(define kappa 0.5)   ; mean-reversion speed
(define theta 0.05)  ; long-run mean (5%)
(define sigma 0.02)  ; volatility
(define dt 0.01)     ; time step

; Simulate a path from r0=0.08 (above mean) with fixed shocks
(define shocks (list 0.3 -0.5 0.1 -0.2 0.4 -0.8 0.2 -0.1 0.6 -0.3))

(define (simulate r shocks)
  (if (null? shocks) (list)
      (let ((next (vasicek-step r kappa theta sigma dt (car shocks))))
        (cons next (simulate next (cdr shocks))))))

(define path (simulate 0.08 shocks))
(display "Starting rate: 0.08") (newline)
(display "Path: ")
(for-each (lambda (r) (display (exact->inexact r)) (display " ")) path)
(newline)

; Expected value: E[r(t)] = theta + (r0-theta)*exp(-kappa*t)
(define (vasicek-mean r0 t)
  (+ theta (* (- r0 theta) (exp (* (- kappa) t)))))

(display "E[r(1)] from r0=0.08: ")
(display (exact->inexact (vasicek-mean 0.08 1.0))) (newline)
(display "E[r(5)] from r0=0.08: ")
(display (exact->inexact (vasicek-mean 0.08 5.0)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

def vasicek_step(r, kappa, theta, sigma, dt, z):
    return r + kappa*(theta - r)*dt + sigma*math.sqrt(dt)*z

kappa, theta, sigma, dt = 0.5, 0.05, 0.02, 0.01
shocks = [0.3, -0.5, 0.1, -0.2, 0.4, -0.8, 0.2, -0.1, 0.6, -0.3]

r = 0.08
path = []
for z in shocks:
    r = vasicek_step(r, kappa, theta, sigma, dt, z)
    path.append(r)

print("Starting rate: 0.08")
print("Path:", " ".join(f"{x:.5f}" for x in path))

# Analytical expected value
def vasicek_mean(r0, t):
    return theta + (r0 - theta)*math.exp(-kappa*t)

print(f"E[r(1)] from r0=0.08: {vasicek_mean(0.08, 1.0):.6f}")
print(f"E[r(5)] from r0=0.08: {vasicek_mean(0.08, 5.0):.6f}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. CIR Model -->
    <h3>CIR model</h3>
    <p>Cox-Ingersoll-Ross fixes the negativity problem: dr = &#x3BA;(&#x3B8; &#x2212; r)dt + &#x3C3;&#x221A;r dW. The &#x221A;r term shrinks volatility as rates approach zero, preventing them from going negative (provided 2&#x3BA;&#x3B8; &#x2265; &#x3C3;&#xB2;, the Feller condition). Same mean-reversion, better boundary behavior.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; CIR model: dr = kappa*(theta - r)*dt + sigma*sqrt(r)*dW
; Key difference from Vasicek: volatility scales with sqrt(r)

(define (cir-step r kappa theta sigma dt z)
  (let ((new-r (+ r (* kappa (- theta r) dt)
                   (* sigma (sqrt (max r 0)) (sqrt dt) z))))
    (max new-r 0)))  ; floor at zero for numerical safety

(define kappa 0.5)
(define theta 0.05)
(define sigma 0.1)
(define dt 0.01)

; Feller condition: 2*kappa*theta >= sigma^2
(define feller (* 2 kappa theta))
(define sigma-sq (* sigma sigma))
(display "2*kappa*theta = ") (display feller) (newline)
(display "sigma^2 = ") (display sigma-sq) (newline)
(display "Feller satisfied? ") (display (>= feller sigma-sq)) (newline)

; Simulate from r0=0.01 (near zero — this is where CIR matters)
(define shocks (list 0.5 -1.2 0.8 -0.3 1.0 -0.6 0.2 0.9 -0.4 0.1))

(define (simulate-cir r shocks)
  (if (null? shocks) (list)
      (let ((next (cir-step r kappa theta sigma dt (car shocks))))
        (cons next (simulate-cir next (cdr shocks))))))

(define path (simulate-cir 0.01 shocks))
(display "CIR path from r0=0.01: ") (newline)
(for-each (lambda (r) (display (exact->inexact r)) (display " ")) path)
(newline)
(display "All non-negative? ")
(display (not (memq #f (map (lambda (r) (>= r 0)) path))))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

def cir_step(r, kappa, theta, sigma, dt, z):
    new_r = r + kappa*(theta-r)*dt + sigma*math.sqrt(max(r,0))*math.sqrt(dt)*z
    return max(new_r, 0)

kappa, theta, sigma, dt = 0.5, 0.05, 0.1, 0.01
feller = 2*kappa*theta
print(f"2*kappa*theta = {feller}, sigma^2 = {sigma**2}")
print(f"Feller satisfied? {feller >= sigma**2}")

shocks = [0.5, -1.2, 0.8, -0.3, 1.0, -0.6, 0.2, 0.9, -0.4, 0.1]
r = 0.01
path = []
for z in shocks:
    r = cir_step(r, kappa, theta, sigma, dt, z)
    path.append(r)

print("CIR path from r0=0.01:")
print(" ".join(f"{x:.5f}" for x in path))
print(f"All non-negative? {all(x >= 0 for x in path)}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 3. HJM Framework -->
    <h3>HJM framework</h3>
    <p>Heath-Jarrow-Morton models the entire <strong>forward rate curve</strong> instead of a single short rate. The forward rate f(t,T) is the rate locked in at time t for instantaneous borrowing at T. The drift is not free: no-arbitrage forces it to equal &#x3C3;(t,T) times the integral of &#x3C3; from t to T. This <strong>drift condition</strong> is the heart of HJM.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; HJM drift condition: mu(t,T) = sigma(t,T) * integral_t^T sigma(t,s) ds
; For constant volatility sigma, the drift is sigma^2 * (T-t)

(define (hjm-drift sigma t cap-t)
  (* sigma sigma (- cap-t t)))

; Forward rate evolution: df(t,T) = mu(t,T)*dt + sigma*dW
(define (forward-rate-step f sigma t cap-t dt z)
  (+ f (* (hjm-drift sigma t cap-t) dt) (* sigma (sqrt dt) z)))

(define sigma 0.01)  ; forward rate volatility
(define dt 0.25)     ; quarterly steps

; Evolve 1-year forward rate over 4 quarters
(define shocks (list 0.5 -0.3 0.8 -0.2))
(define f0 0.05)  ; initial 1-year forward rate

(define (evolve f t cap-t shocks)
  (if (null? shocks) (list)
      (let ((next (forward-rate-step f sigma t cap-t dt (car shocks))))
        (cons next (evolve next (+ t dt) cap-t (cdr shocks))))))

(define path (evolve f0 0 1.0 shocks))
(display "Forward rate f(t,1) path: ") (newline)
(for-each (lambda (r) (display (exact->inexact r)) (display " ")) path)
(newline)

; Bond price: P(t,T) = exp(-integral_t^T f(t,s) ds)
; Approximate: P ≈ exp(-f * (T-t))
(define (bond-price f tau)
  (exp (* (- f) tau)))

(display "Bond price P(0,1) at f=5%: ")
(display (exact->inexact (bond-price 0.05 1.0)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

def hjm_drift(sigma, t, T):
    return sigma**2 * (T - t)

def forward_rate_step(f, sigma, t, T, dt, z):
    return f + hjm_drift(sigma, t, T)*dt + sigma*math.sqrt(dt)*z

sigma, dt = 0.01, 0.25
shocks = [0.5, -0.3, 0.8, -0.2]
f, t, T = 0.05, 0, 1.0

path = []
for z in shocks:
    f = forward_rate_step(f, sigma, t, T, dt, z)
    t += dt
    path.append(f)

print("Forward rate f(t,1) path:")
print(" ".join(f"{x:.6f}" for x in path))

# Bond price approximation
bond_price = math.exp(-0.05 * 1.0)
print(f"Bond price P(0,1) at f=5%: {bond_price:.6f}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 4. Interest Rate Derivatives -->
    <h3>Pricing caps and floors</h3>
    <p>A <strong>caplet</strong> pays max(r &#x2212; K, 0) at maturity: insurance against rates rising above the strike K. A <strong>floorlet</strong> pays max(K &#x2212; r, 0): insurance against rates falling. A cap is a strip of caplets; a floor is a strip of floorlets. In the Vasicek model, the distribution of future rates is normal, so caplet prices have Black-like closed forms.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Caplet and floorlet payoffs
; Caplet: max(r - K, 0), Floorlet: max(K - r, 0)

(define (caplet-payoff r strike notional tau)
  (* notional tau (max (- r strike) 0)))

(define (floorlet-payoff r strike notional tau)
  (* notional tau (max (- strike r) 0)))

(define notional 1000000)  ; $1M notional
(define strike 0.05)       ; 5% strike
(define tau 0.25)          ; quarterly period

; Rate scenarios
(define rates (list 0.03 0.04 0.05 0.06 0.07 0.08))

(display "Rate    Caplet      Floorlet") (newline)
(for-each
  (lambda (r)
    (display (exact->inexact r)) (display "    ")
    (display (exact->inexact (caplet-payoff r strike notional tau)))
    (display "    ")
    (display (exact->inexact (floorlet-payoff r strike notional tau)))
    (newline))
  rates)

; Cap-floor parity: caplet - floorlet = forward - strike (times notional*tau)
(newline) (display "--- Cap-Floor Parity ---") (newline)
(define r-test 0.07)
(define cap (caplet-payoff r-test strike notional tau))
(define flr (floorlet-payoff r-test strike notional tau))
(display "Caplet - Floorlet = ")
(display (exact->inexact (- cap flr))) (newline)
(display "Notional*tau*(r-K) = ")
(display (exact->inexact (* notional tau (- r-test strike))))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Caplet and floorlet payoffs
def caplet(r, K, notional, tau):
    return notional * tau * max(r - K, 0)

def floorlet(r, K, notional, tau):
    return notional * tau * max(K - r, 0)

notional, strike, tau = 1_000_000, 0.05, 0.25
rates = [0.03, 0.04, 0.05, 0.06, 0.07, 0.08]

print("Rate    Caplet       Floorlet")
for r in rates:
    print(f"{r:.2f}    {caplet(r, strike, notional, tau):>10.2f}    {floorlet(r, strike, notional, tau):>10.2f}")

# Cap-floor parity
r_test = 0.07
cap = caplet(r_test, strike, notional, tau)
flr = floorlet(r_test, strike, notional, tau)
print(f"\\nCaplet - Floorlet = {cap - flr:.2f}")
print(f"Notional*tau*(r-K) = {notional*tau*(r_test - strike):.2f}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 5. Vasicek Bond Pricing -->
    <h3>Bond pricing under Vasicek</h3>
    <p>With Vasicek dynamics, the price of a zero-coupon bond has a closed-form solution: P(t,T) = A(&#x3C4;)e^(-B(&#x3C4;)r), where &#x3C4; = T&#x2212;t, B(&#x3C4;) = (1&#x2212;e^(-&#x3BA;&#x3C4;))/&#x3BA;, and A depends on &#x3B8;, &#x3C3;, &#x3BA;. This gives the entire yield curve from a single state variable r.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Vasicek zero-coupon bond price: P(t,T) = A(tau)*exp(-B(tau)*r)
; B(tau) = (1 - exp(-kappa*tau)) / kappa
; A(tau) = exp(((B-tau)*(kappa^2*theta - sigma^2/2))/kappa^2 - sigma^2*B^2/(4*kappa))

(define kappa 0.5)
(define theta 0.05)
(define sigma 0.02)

(define (B-func tau)
  (/ (- 1 (exp (* (- kappa) tau))) kappa))

(define (A-func tau)
  (let ((b (B-func tau)))
    (exp (- (* (/ (- b tau)
                  (* kappa kappa))
               (- (* kappa kappa theta) (/ (* sigma sigma) 2)))
            (/ (* sigma sigma b b) (* 4 kappa))))))

(define (vasicek-bond-price r tau)
  (* (A-func tau) (exp (* (- (B-func tau)) r))))

; Current short rate
(define r0 0.06)

; Yield curve: price and yield for maturities 1 to 10
(display "Maturity  Price    Yield") (newline)
(define (show-curve tau)
  (if (> tau 10) (display "")
      (let* ((p (vasicek-bond-price r0 tau))
             (y (- (/ (log p) tau))))
        (display tau) (display "y       ")
        (display (exact->inexact p)) (display "  ")
        (display (exact->inexact y)) (newline)
        (show-curve (+ tau 1)))))

(show-curve 1)
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

kappa, theta, sigma = 0.5, 0.05, 0.02

def B(tau):
    return (1 - math.exp(-kappa*tau)) / kappa

def A(tau):
    b = B(tau)
    return math.exp((b-tau)*(kappa**2*theta - sigma**2/2)/kappa**2
                    - sigma**2*b**2/(4*kappa))

def vasicek_bond_price(r, tau):
    return A(tau) * math.exp(-B(tau)*r)

r0 = 0.06
print("Maturity  Price      Yield")
for tau in range(1, 11):
    p = vasicek_bond_price(r0, tau)
    y = -math.log(p) / tau
    print(f"{tau:>4}y     {p:.6f}  {y:.6f}")
`} />
